6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Both exchanges calculate funding rates using 8-hour intervals based on the premium/discount between perpetual and spot prices. Binance uses a time-weighted average price (TWAP) mechanism with interest rate components, while Gate.io employs a similar methodology but with different smoothing parameters. Binance's deeper liquidity typically results in more stable funding rates for major pairs, whereas Gate.io's rates can be more volatile on lower-cap tokens due to thinner orderbooks. Both platforms cap funding rates at ±0.75% per interval during extreme market conditions."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rate opportunities?","answer":"Binance provides more stable rates on major pairs due to deeper liquidity, while Gate.io offers higher volatility opportunities on micro-cap tokens. The choice depends on your risk tolerance and target assets."},{"question":"How do trading fees impact funding arbitrage profitability?","answer":"Gate.io's 0.015% maker fee gives it a 0.005% advantage over Binance per trade. This difference can significantly impact profitability when frequently opening and closing positions for rate arbitrage."},{"question":"Are there differences in funding rate calculation methodology?","answer":"Both use 8-hour intervals and similar TWAP-based calculations, but Binance's insurance fund and deeper liquidity provide more predictable rate patterns. Gate.io's rates may spike more dramatically on low-liquidity pairs."},{"question":"Which platform is more reliable for large funding arbitrage positions?","answer":"Binance's superior liquidity and $1B+ insurance fund make it more suitable for large positions. Gate.io works better for smaller positions on a wider range of tokens but may have slippage issues with size."}]}]
